		<section>
			<section.front>
				<doc.title toc-guid="Id7206532682311ea83aee46e6decbb85">
					<head parent="doc.title">
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<label.name>§ </label.name>
						<label.designator>9:9.</label.designator>
						<headtext>Admissions—Judicial</headtext>
						<eos/>
						<eop/>
					</head>
				</doc.title>
			</section.front>
			<section.body>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Under <cite.query w-src-number="0287017168" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-8-821" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ife0d4c6074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-8-821</cite.query>, parties can use admissions contained in pleadings of an opponent <begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/>“[w]ithout offering the same in evidence.”<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<end.quote refid="QT_0002"/> Such admissions in judicio bind the party so that they cannot put up evidence over objection to contradict such admissions, unless the admissions are properly withdrawn.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I79df72f074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>
						<?page no="291"?>] A proper amendment that does not incorporate the prior allegations prevents the prior admission from becoming a binding admission in judicio.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I79df72f174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] A judicial admission is conclusive and cannot be denied or disputed.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I79df72f274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>] <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“However, if a party amends its pleadings to withdraw the admissions, it may then introduce evidence contravening the admissions. <eos/>
						<bos/>If such contradictory evidence is admitted, even over the objection of the other party, then … such evidence may be deemed to amend the pleadings to withdraw the admissions.”<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I79df72f374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>] Importantly, only admissions of fact, not opinion or conclusions of law, may be considered as evidence under this rule. <eos/>
						<bos/>For instance, an admission that a party executed a personal guaranty does not mean that the party admitted the legal effect of the guaranty.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I79df72f474d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>The Georgia Court of Appeals held that it was reversible error for a trial court not to allow the plaintiff to cross-examine the defendant about admissions in the defendant&apos;s answer without first putting the entire answer in evidence.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I79df9a0074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">6</footnote.reference>] The text of the Code section refers to “pleadings,” but it may also be applicable to a statement of facts included as part of a summary judgment brief.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I79df9a0174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">7</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>On the other hand, exhibits attached to a complaint[<footnote.reference refid="I79df9a0274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">8</footnote.reference>] and affidavits attached to a brief for summary judgment are not judicial admissions.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I79df9a0374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">9</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<?page no="292"?>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Generally, a stipulation of facts is only conclusive in that case, but it may also be properly introduced as an admission in another case between the parties that involves the same issues.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I79df9a0474d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">10</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>To be binding, a judicial admission must be one of fact and not merely a party&apos;s opinion or conclusion as to law or fact.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I79df9a0574d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">11</footnote.reference>] Thus, an answer to a complaint which states as an affirmative defense that the defendant executed a note as an accommodation party is not a binding admission of fact which would support a summary judgment order. <eos/>
						<bos/>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017168" w-serial-number="1991206376" w-seq-number="00026" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ife1562b274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Gunter v. Hamilton Bank of Upper East Tennessee</ital>
						</cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I79dfc11074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">12</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Court of Appeals reversed a summary judgment against the defendant based upon such an admission. <eos/>
						<bos/>Similarly, in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017168" w-serial-number="2003161306" w-seq-number="00028" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ife16260274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Flynn v. Mack</ital>
						</cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I79dfc11174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">13</footnote.reference>] the court held that the plaintiff&apos;s admission that there was slight evidence supporting the jury&apos;s verdict against her was an opinion on the facts and not an admission of fact and did not constitute an admission in judicio.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>A defendant&apos;s answer in a complaint to modify custody that the defendant was a resident of Colorado effectively divested the Florida court that originally rendered the divorce decree of jurisdiction and acted as a bar to the defendant&apos;s motion to dismiss.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I79dfc11274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">14</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
			</section.body>
		</section>
