				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287017168" w-serial-number="1984141789" w-seq-number="00023" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ife14032274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Aiken v. Department of Transp., 171 Ga. App. 154, 319 S.E.2d 58 (1984)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>Also, the statement must not be an opinion as to the legal effect of facts. <eos/>
							<bos/>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017168" w-serial-number="1985134422" w-seq-number="00024" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ife14514274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Scott v. Jefferson, 174 Ga. App. 651, 331 S.E.2d 1 (1985)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>Admission in statement of facts on summary judgment that the plaintiffs breached the contract did not constitute an admission in judicio as it was a legal conclusion or opinion and not an admission of fact. <eos/>
							<bos/>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017168" w-serial-number="2018318744" w-seq-number="00025" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ife14c67274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Bollers v. Noir Enterprises, Inc., 297 Ga. App. 435, 677 S.E.2d 338 (2009)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
				</footnote.body>
			</footnote>
